org.jtuples

Class Triple<A,B,C>

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.jtuples.AbstractTuple
      • org.jtuples.Triple<A,B,C>
  • Type Parameters:
    A - the type of the first element of the triple
    B - the type of the second element of the triple
    C - the type of the third element of the triple
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Tuple

    public final class Triple<A,B,C>
extends AbstractTuple
    Represents a mathematical ordered triple of objects. The order in which the objects appear in the triple is significant: the ordered triple (a, b, c) is different from the ordered triple (b, a, c) unless a and b are equal.
    Author:
    Andre Santos

      • shiftLeft

        public Triple<B,C,A> shiftLeft()
        Returns a new tuple, with the members shifted to the left by one position. This operation has a wrapping behaviour, meaning that the member that would be excluded by the shift instead occupies the new open position. For instance, calling ((1, 2, 3)).shiftLeft() would yield the tuple (2, 3, 1).
        Returns:
        a tuple shifted to the left, wrapping around

      • shiftLeft

        public <V> Triple<B,C,V> shiftLeft(V value)
        Returns a new tuple, with the members shifted to the left by one position. The given value occupies the new open position, after shifting the original members. For instance, calling ((1, 2, 3)).shiftLeft(4) would yield the tuple (2, 3, 4).
        Type Parameters:
        V - the type of the new member to be inserted
        Parameters:
        value - the new member to be inserted
        Returns:
        a tuple shifted to the left, with the new member given

      • shiftRight

        public Triple<C,A,B> shiftRight()
        Returns a new tuple, with the members shifted to the right by one position. This operation has a wrapping behaviour, meaning that the member that would be excluded by the shift instead occupies the new open position. For instance, calling ((1, 2, 3)).shiftRight() would yield the tuple (3, 1, 2).
        Returns:
        a tuple shifted to the right, wrapping around

      • shiftRight

        public <V> Triple<V,A,B> shiftRight(V value)
        Returns a new tuple, with the members shifted to the right by one position. The given value occupies the new open position, after shifting the original members. For instance, calling ((1, 2, 3)).shiftRight(0) would yield the tuple (0, 1, 2).
        Type Parameters:
        V - the type of the new member to be inserted
        Parameters:
        value - the new member to be inserted
        Returns:

      • applyFirst

        public <R> Triple<R,B,C> applyFirst(Function<A,R> function)
        Returns a new triple, transforming the first member of this triple. The first member of the new triple is the result of applying the given function to the first member of this triple. The second and third members are preserved.
        Type Parameters:
        R - the type of the function's result
        Parameters:
        function - the function used to transform the first member
        Returns:
        a triple with the result of function as the first member
